---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Field rules">
  <section class="page-head wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">Protect the experience</p>
    <h1>Wild means it does not perform for us.</h1>
    <p>
      Keep these distances and decisions simple enough that the kids can enforce
      them too.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section wrap rules-grid">
    <article class="distance-card turtle">
      <span>10 feet</span>
      <h2>Sea turtles · honu</h2>
      <p>
        Recommended minimum on land and in water. Never touch, feed, chase,
        block, or wake.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="distance-card seal">
      <span>50 feet</span>
      <h2>Hawaiian monk seals</h2>
      <p>Stay behind barriers. Mothers and pups need at least 150 feet.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="distance-card dolphin">
      <span>50 yards</span>
      <h2>Spinner dolphins</h2>
      <p>
        Federal law prohibits swimming with, approaching, or remaining within 50
        yards.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="distance-card whale">
      <span>100 yards</span>
      <h2>Humpback whales</h2>
      <p>
        Federal law in Hawaiʻi. July is outside the normal November–April
        season.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section wrap field-rules">
    <article>
      <span class="rule-number">01</span>
      <div>
        <h2>Ocean first, plan second</h2>
        <p>
          If surf, current, visibility, weather, signage, or family comfort says
          no, remain on land. Morning is often calmer, never guaranteed safe.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="rule-number">02</span>
      <div>
        <h2>Feet off the reef</h2>
        <p>
          Do not stand on coral, handle animals, remove shells, or “rescue”
          resting wildlife.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="rule-number">03</span>
      <div>
        <h2>Ask before picking</h2>
        <p>
          Fruit requires owner permission and positive identification. Public
          abundance does not erase private property, reserve rules, spray, or
          roadside contamination.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
    <article>
      <span class="rule-number">04</span>
      <div>
        <h2>Report, do not intervene</h2>
        <p>
          For sick, injured, stranded, or dead marine wildlife, call NOAA's
          statewide hotline:
          <a href="tel:+18882569840">888-256-9840</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="source-panel wrap">
    <p>
      Rules verified against NOAA Fisheries and Hawaiʻi DLNR on June 27, 2026.
    </p>
    <a
      class="button primary"
      href="https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/pacific-islands/marine-life-viewing-guidelines/viewing-marine-wildlife-hawaii"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noreferrer">Open NOAA guidance</a
    >
  </section>
</Layout>
